t of the things you want to do today. Check them off when you have done them.',505,''),(4824,'\0',125,'    b. Write two letters to relatives or friends.',505,''),(4825,'\0',126,'    c. Keep a daily record of your activities for 2 weeks.',505,''),(4826,'\0',127,'    d. Write an invitation to someone.',505,''),(4827,'\0',128,'    e. Write a thank-you note.',505,''),(4828,'\0',129,'    f. Write a story about something you have done with your family.',505,''),(4829,'\0',130,'    g. Write about the activities of your den.',505,''),(4830,'\0',131,'    h. Complete the Character Connection for Honesty.',505,''),(4831,'\0',132,'      -Know. Tell what made it difficult to be clear and accurate as you wrote details and kept records, and tell what could tempt you to write something that was not exactly true. Define honesty.',505,''),(4832,'\0',133,'      -Commit. Tell why it is important to be honest and trustworthy with yourself and with others. Imagine you had reported something inaccurately and tell how you could set the record straight. Give reasons that honest reporting will earn the trust of others.',505,''),(4833,'\0',134,'      -Practice. While doing the requirement for this achievement, be honest when you are writing about real events.',505,''),(4834,'\0',135,'19. SHAVINGS AND CHIPS (Page 146)\r\n   Do all four requirements.',505,''),(4835,'\0',136,'    a. Know the safety rules for handling a knife.',505,''),(4836,'\0',137,'    b. Show that you know how to take care of and use a pocketknife.',505,''),(4837,'\0',138,'    c. Make a carving with a pocketknife. Work with your den leader or other adult when doing this.',505,''),(4838,'\0',139,'    d. Earn the Whittling Chip card.',505,''),(4839,'\0',140,'20. SAWDUST AND NAILS (Page 152)\r\n   Do all three requirements.',505,''),(4840,'\0',141,'    a. Show how to use and take care of four of these tools (Hammer, Hand saw, Hand drill, C-clamp, Wood plane, Pliers, Crescent wrench, Screwdriver, Bench vise, Coping saw, Drill bit)',505,''),(4841,'\0',142,'    b. Build your own tool box.',505,''),(4842,'\0',143,'    c. Use at least two tools listed in requirement (a) to fix something.',505,''),(4843,'\0',144,'21. BUILD A MODEL (Page 156)\r\n   Do requirement g and two other requirements.',505,''),(4844,'\0',145,'    a. Build a model from a kit.',505,''),(4845,'\0',146,'    b. Build a display for one of your models.',505,''),(4846,'\0',147,'    c. Pretend you are planning to change the furniture layout in one of the rooms in your home.',505,''),(4847,'\0',148,'    d. Make a model of a mountain, a meadow, a canyon, or a river.',505,''),(4848,'\0',149,'    e. Go and see a model of a shopping center or new building that is on display somewhere.',505,''),(4849,'\0',150,'    f. Make a model of a rocket, boat, car, or plane.',505,''),(4850,'\0',151,'    g. Complete the Character Connection for Resourcefulness.',505,''),(4851,'\0',152,'      -Know. Review the requirements for this achievement and list the resources you would need to complete them. Then list the materials you could substitute for items that you do not already have. Tell what it means to be resourceful.',505,''),(4852,'\0',153,'      -Commit. After you complete the requirements for this achievement, list any changes that would make the results better if you did these projects again. Tell why it is important to consider all available resources for a project.',505,''),(4853,'\0',154,'      -Practice. While you complete the requirements for this achievement, make notes on which materials worked well in your projects and why.',505,''),(4854,'\0',155,'22. TYING IT ALL UP (Page 162)\r\n   Do five requirements.',505,''),(4855,'\0',156,'    a. Whip the ends of a rope.',505,''),(4856,'\0',157,'    b. Tie a square knot, bowline, sheet bend, two half hitches, and slip knot.  Tell how each knot is used.',505,''),(4857,'\0',158,'    c. Learn how to keep a rope from tangling.',505,''),(4858,'\0',159,'    d. Coil a rope. Throw it, hitting a 2-foot square marker 20 feet away.',505,''),(4859,'\0',160,'    e. Learn a magic rope trick.',505,''),(4860,'\0',161,'    f. Make your own rope.',505,''),(4861,'\0',162,'23. SPORTS, SPORTS, SPORTS (Page 170)\r\n   Do all five requirements.',505,''),(4862,'\0',163,'    a. Learn the rules of and how to play three team sports.',505,''),(4863,'\0',164,'    b. Learn the rules of and how to play two sports in which only one person is on each side.',505,''),(4864,'\0',165,'    c. Take part in one team and one individual sport.',505,''),(4865,'\0',166,'    d. Watch a sport on TV with a parent or some other adult member of your family.',505,''),(4866,'\0',167,'    e. Attend a high school, college, or professional sporting event with your family or your den.',505,''),(4867,'\0',168,'24. BE A LEADER (Page 174)\r\n   Do requirement f and two other requirements.',505,''),(4868,'\0',169,'    a. Help a boy join Cub Scouting, or help a new Cub Scout through the Bobcat trail.',505,''),(4869,'\0',170,'    b. Serve as a denner or assistant denner.',505,''),(4870,'\0',171,'    c. Plan and conduct a den activity with the approval of your den leader.',505,''),(4871,'\0',172,'    d. Tell two people they have done a good job.',505,''),(4872,'\0',173,'    e. Leadership means choosing a way even when not everybody likes your choice.',505,''),(4873,'\0',174,'    f. Complete the Character Connection for Compassion.',505,''),(4874,'\0',175,'      -Know. Tell why, as a leader, it is important to show kindness and concern for other people. List ways leaders show they care about the thoughts and feelings of others.',505,''),(4875,'\0',176,'      -Commit. Tell why a good leader must consider the ideas, abilities, and feelings of others. Tell why it might be hard for a leader to protect another person\'s well-being. Tell ways you can be kind and compassionate.',505,''),(4876,'\0',177,'      -Practice. While you complete the requirements for this achievement, find ways to be kind and considerate of others.',505,''),(4877,'\0',0,'AFTER a Bear Cub Scout earns his Bear Badge he may begin earning Arrow Points in the Electives.\r\n\r\nHe may work on his (Arrow Point Trail) at any time, however he cannot receive Arrow Points until AFTER he has earned the Bear Badge.\r\n\r\nThere is a big difference in the achievements for arrow points for Bear. In this rank the Cub Scout can go back and do requirements from the ACHIEVEMENTS section of the book and use them as requirements for arrow points, as long as they do not count any requirements from achievements that they used to earn the Bear Badge. Unused parts of achievements that were used for the Bear badge may NOT be counted toward Arrow Points.\r\n\r\nThe Achievement requirements and the Elective requirements can be freely mixed to count toward earning arrow points. In the following descriptions, we will use the term (arrow point activities) to refer to either type of requirement.\r\n\r\nGOLD ARROW POINT:\r\n    For the FIRST 10 arrow point activities completed, the Bear Cub earns his GOLD ARROW POINT.\r\nSILVER ARROW POINTS:\r\n    For EACH 10 arrow point activities completed (AFTER HE EARNS THE GOLD ARROW POINT) the Bear Cub earns a SILVER ARROW POINT. \r\n\r\nAs a BEAR Cub Scout, a boy may earn any number of SILVER ARROW POINTS, but he may only earn ONE GOLD ARROW POINT for the first 10 arrow point activities that he completes.',506,'\0'),(4878,'\0',1,'1. SPACE (Page 182)',506,'\0'),(4879,'\0',2,'  a. Identify two constellations and the North Star in the night sky.',506,''),(4880,'\0',3,'  b. Make a pinhole planetarium and show three constellations.',506,''),(4881,'\0',4,'  c. Visit a planetarium.',506,''),(4882,'\0',5,'  d. Build a model of a rocket or space satellite.',506,''),(4883,'\0',6,'  e. Read and talk about at least one man-made satellite and one natural one.',506,''),(4884,'\0',7,'  f. Find a picture of another planet in our solar system. Explain how it is different from Earth.',506,''),(4885,'\0',8,'2. WEATHER (Page 184)\r\n   This elective is also part of the Cub Scout World Conservation Award.',506,'\0'),(4886,'\0',9,'  a. Learn how to read an outdoor thermometer. Put one outdoors and read it at the same time every day for two weeks. Keep a record of each day\'s temperature and a description of the weather each day (fair skies, rain, fog, snow, etc.).',506,''),(4887,'\0',10,'  b. Build a weather vane. Record wind direction every day at the same hour for two weeks. Keep a record of the weather for each day.',506,''),(4888,'\0',11,'  c. Make a rain gauge.',506,''),(4889,'\0',12,'  d. Find out what a barometer is and how it works. Tell your den about it. Tell what \'relative humidity\' means.',506,''),(4890,'\0',13,'  e. Learn to identify three different kinds of clouds. Estimate their heights.',506,''),(4891,'\0',14,'  f. Watch the weather forecast on TV every day for two weeks. Describe three different symbols used on weather maps. Keep a record of how many times the weather forecast is correct.',506,''),(4892,'\0',15,'3. RADIO (Page 190)',506,'\0'),(4893,'\0',16,'  a. Build a crystal or diode radio. Check with your local craft or hobby shop or the nearest Scout shop that carries a crystal radio kit. It is all right to use a kit.',506,''),(4894,'\0',17,'  b. Make and operate a battery powered radio, following the directions with the kit.',506,''),(4895,'\0',18,'4. ELECTRICITY (Page 192)',506,'\0'),(4896,'\0',19,'  a. Wire a buzzer or doorbell.',506,''),(4897,'\0',20,'  b. Make an electric buzzer game.',506,''),(4898,'\0',21,'  c. Make a simple bar or horseshoe electromagnet.',506,''),(4899,'\0',22,'  d. Use a simple electric motor.',506,''),(4900,'\0',23,'  e. Make a crane with an electromagnetic lift.',506,''),(4901,'\0',24,'5. BOATS (Page 196)',506,'\0'),(4902,'\0',25,'  a. Help an adult rig and sail a real boat. (Wear your PFD.)',506,''),(4903,'\0',26,'  b. Help an adult repair a real boat or canoe.',506,''),(4904,'\0',27,'  c. Know the flag signals for storm warnings.',506,''),(4905,'\0',28,'  d. Help an adult repair a boat dock.',506,''),(4906,'\0',29,'  e. With an adult on board, and both wearing PFDs, row a boat around a 100-yard course that has two turns. Demonstrate forward strokes, turns to both sides, and backstrokes.',506,''),(4907,'\0',30,'6. AIRCRAFT (Page 202)',506,'\0'),(4908,'\0',31,'  a. Identify five different kinds of aircraft, in flight if possible, or from models or photos.',506,''),(4909,'\0',32,'  b. Ride in a commercial airplane.',506,''),(4910,'\0',33,'  c. Explain how a hot air balloon works.',506,''),(4911,'\0',34,'  d. Build and fly a model airplane. (You may use a kit. Every time you do this differently, it counts as a completed project.)',506,''),(4912,'\0',35,'  e. Sketch and label an airplane showing the direction of forces acting on it (lift, drag, and load).',506,''),(4913,'\0',36,'  f. Make a list of some of the things a helicopter can do that other kinds of airplanes can\'t. Draw or cut out a picture of a helicopter and label the parts.',506,''),(4914,'\0',37,'  g. Build and display a scale airplane model. You may use a kit or build it from plans.',506,''),(4915,'\0',38,'7. THINGS THAT GO (Page 206)',506,'\0'),(4916,'\0',39,'  a. With an adult\'s help, make a scooter or a Cubmobile. Know the safety rules.',506,''),(4917,'\0',40,'  b. With an adult\'s help, make a windmill.',506,''),(4918,'\0',41,'  c. With an adult\'s help, make a waterwheel.',506,''),(4919,'\0',42,'  d. Make an invention of your own design that goes.',506,''),(4920,'\0',43,'8. CUB SCOUT BAND (Page 210)',506,'\0'),(4921,'\0',44,'  a. Make and play a homemade musical instrument - cigar-box banjo, washtub bull fiddle, a drum or rhythm set, tambourine. etc.',506,''),(4922,'\0',45,'  b. Learn to play two familiar tunes on any musical instrument.',506,''),(4923,'\0',46,'  c. Play in a den band using homemade or regular musical instruments. Play a